    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Many voters will no doubt make their decisions in this election based on one issue, like abortion or gun control, and special-interest groups are spending large amounts of money and hours ''educating'' the public about their causes (news article, Oct. 22). Although these groups are a vital part of a democracy, we must remember that there is often a fuzzy line between education and scare tactics.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Many voters will no doubt make their decisions in this election based on one issue, like abortion or gun control, and special-interest groups are spending large amounts of money and hours ''educating'' the public about their causes (news article, Oct. 22). Although these groups are a vital part of a democracy, we must remember that there is often a fuzzy line between education and scare tactics.</p>
        <p>We shouldn't have to scare people to the voting booth. People should vote because they believe strongly in the issues or the candidate. They should vote because they have the right to vote.</p>
        <p>CARRIE FERNANDEZ  Brooklyn, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
